[ Free Game Series ] 👀
Silhouettes can instantly elevate your storytelling. Here's how:

Step 1: BACKLIGHTING your subject is key. Basically, you want your background to be brighter than your foreground subject.

Step 2: SETTINGS play a key role in landing a solid silhouette. I prefer shooting in Manual Mode (M) for complete creative control.
Dial in these settings:
F-Stop: f/4.0
Shutter Speed: 1/250 - 1/500 sec.
ISO: 400-800

Step 3. FIND an interesting scene/frame/composition.

Step 4. Practice,  practice,  practice. 😤

Let's discuss!!

#streetsoul
#LessIsMore
#pointandshoot
#ricohgr2

[ Free Game Series ] 👀
"GESTURE" is typically a movement made/displayed by your subject, object. BUT,  I also believe, gesture is the feeling you experience in that single moment or frame. Joy, sadness, curiosity, empathy etc. So how do we lookout for gesture when we're shooting?

Try these tips:

1. START SMALL. Look for a simple object like a bent street sign that seems out of place, or someone maybe tying their shoes while people walk around them. These are gestures that carry a "unique" quality with them.

2. ANTICIPATE the movement your subject may or may not make. This is great practice for improving your timing and staying present. Sometimes you get lucky.🙂📸

3. Change your POV (point of view). When you approach a scene from a different angle, the gesture just might change.

4. Practice, practice, practice.

Let's discuss!!

Let's address 3 MYTHS in Photography
.
.
There's already too much to think about as a photographer,  creative, entrepreneur, social media strategist, etc... And these 3 things take up too much room in our minds.

MYTH 1 - Buying the newest or big brand name cameras guarantees results.👀

MYTH 2 - You'll make great images every time you shoot.👀

MYTH 3 - Hoarding or holding onto your work for the "right" moment is a strategy. 👀

SOLUTIONS:

1. Master the camera you have currently. Period.

2. Focus on creating a body of work through daily practice.

3. SHARE. YOUR. WORK.🔥

Let's discuss!

#streetphotographytips #photographybusiness

CINEMATIC IMAGES can take our mind into magical places.

These simple adjustments can help right now.

1. Focus on story first
2. Shoot into the light
3. Time of day & weather are key

BONUS: Find the colours in your scene that connect to specific emotions .👀

#Streetsoul

Create MOTION BLUR on purpose...
Give your static image energy with these small adjustments when you're out shooting.

1. USE A SLOW SHUTTER SPEED. A good range to start: 1/2 Sec - 1/60th sec. Remember to adjust your F-Stop & ISO accordingly. Tweek to your liking through experimentation.👀

2. FOCUS ON A SINGLE SUBJECT (even in a busy frame). Your camera settings are in the range that we just spoke about above.👀

3. LOCATION MATTERS. A "unique" backdrop means you're 50% of the way there! Now, simply wait for subjects to pass through your frame. 👀

4. BONUS TIP. Patience through practice. 👀

Watchu think? 🙏🏽

NEW VIDEO UP!
Have you shot with an old DigiCam before?

The pursuit of creating timeless images with whatever camera I have access to has been a driving force thru my photography journey.

In this video I make street images with the #CanonPowerShot SD1400 IS point & shoot digi cam. This camera was released in 2010... over 13 years ago!

The big selling points? Extremely compact. A 14Mp sensor resolution, lens focal range 28-112mm.

Overall, I my user experience for street was just ok. Though it was very discreet and compact, the ergonomic were not well designed. No option to shoot RAW was disappointing. The image render time was below average at 1 second per exposure, shooting multiple exposures was out of the question. I was surprised that I enjoyed using the zoom feature. I found that I rather enjoyed 50mm and roughly 90 mm for street.

Not surprised by any of these findings. But I did love experimenting with a new cam, 13 years old or not.

This is streetsoul.

Recently, @tonyxtones and I had the honour of working with @takethettc. The goal was to create a design that would carry feelings of nostalgia as we say farewell to the Scarborough Rapid Transit Line - SRT LINE 3. (March 22, 1985 - July 24, 2023).

Designed by Scarborough's very own Anthony Gebrehiwot - @tonyxtones, an award-winning Portrait Photographer, Afrofuturist, Multi-Media, and Graphic Designer. It was lovely to listen to his perspective on what LINE 3 meant to him growing up.

For me, the Creative Director hat was refreshing to wear. It was fulfilling to help move ideas forward that we believed in making this collaboration one to remember.

It's also important to point out that a portion of the proceeds from the sales of this limited-edition sweatshirt will go towards United Way Greater Toronto - @uwgreaterto.

Many thanks to @scarboroughtees for printing all the crewnecks. They look 🔥.

You can join in the farewell celebrations TOMORROW Saturday, Sept. 23rd 11:30 a.m. to 4:30 p.m. at Scarborough Centre Station as we all reflect on 38 years of memories. Special guest speakers, local food vendors, a DJ, local merchandise, host a raffle, giveaways, and much more! The SRT trains will be in the station, and you’ll be able to walk through the cars. 👀

Location: Scarborough Centre Station – 290 Borough Drive

Date: Saturday, September 23, 2023

Time: 11:30 am to 4:00 pm

Attendees: This is a public event

This Fall brings with it... A NEW CAMERA FOR ME... FINALLY!

I made the jump to the #RicohGRIIIx. I know, I'm last to the party. Oh well. I love the feel, and image quality and as of this video, my 2 favourite effects are "NEGATIVE FILM" and "HARD Black & White".

What hasn't been written about this camera? The 40mm focal length? It's all been said on YouTube BUT I'm saying, it's perfect for me. I love a good challenge, it brings with it change. So this focal length is sparking new ideas for me.

Sometimes a revamp is necessary for all of us.

I made all of these images throughout the video with the Ricoh GR IIIx point-and-shoot camera.

I hope you enjoy this video and the images as well! Don't forget to subscribe to my NEW newsletter if you dig the convos we have.

Today, I'm giving away 3 prints as a thank you for your ongoing support of my work. LINK IN BIO.

Here’s the great part… It’s super easy to potentially win one. Follow these simple steps below:
Head to Youtube...

1. Like this video.
2. Comment on which print you liked and why.
3. Follow me on Youtube: @tahaphoto

That’s it! You’re done.

Today's video is about a couple of things, but let me start off by saying this... PRINT YOUR WORK. You can learn so much by seeing your work in the flesh. Touching it, analyzing its colours and tones. Annnnd, it's so cheap and quick to try it out today.

I attempted a batch of 4x6 prints with "beginner's" paper stock (180gsm), and I'm pretty happy with them. I learned a lot about the various types that can really bring out the greatness in your work. I break them down in the video. So, what camera did I shoot with to create these prints?

Over the last month or so, I’ve been shooting with the RICOH GR IIIx. The focal length on the GRIIIx is 40mm so, it’s a bit of an adjustment for me coming from the Ricoh GR II's 28mm focal length. With that said, I love it! I love the challenge it's given me on the street. I feel more connected to my environment.

I hope you enjoy the video, and I hope you win a print!

This is streetsoul.

PERSPECTIVE

In photography, your perspective is subjective... BUT we can all agree that different perspectives give us options.

The next time you're out shooting, try making a mental note of these 3 words:

HIGH (a perspective from above or looking up)
EYE (a POV from eye level 👀) 
LOW (a perspective from below or looking down)

No need to overthink or overshoot.

Stay curious and open-minded to the possibilities of your environment.
